{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f58708a9-74dd-453b-84f3-8edef2865377","content":"In .NET 10, the iOS-specific `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with a **cross-platform** `SafeAreaRegions` property directly on `Page`.\n\n**Old (.NET 9):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\n**New (.NET 10):**\n```xml\n<ContentPage SafeAreaRegions=\"All\">\n```\n\nYou can drop the `xmlns:ios` namespace if it was only used for that. The `SafeAreaRegions` enum also supports granular values — `Top`, `Bottom`, `Left`, `Right` — which you can combine:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage SafeAreaRegions=\"Top,Bottom\">\n```\n\nUse `None` to opt out entirely.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"9ebbeba2-3ed8-446c-a05a-95d628420f32","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about a .NET MAUI migration issue from .NET 9 to .NET 10 regarding safe area handling on iOS. This is a known breaking change in .NET 10 MAUI.\n\nIn .NET 10, the `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` attached property was removed/deprecated. The new approach is to use the `SafeAreaRegions` property on `Page` (or layouts), which is a cross-platform property.\n\nLet me provide the correct answer based on my knowledge of .NET MAUI .NET 10 changes.\n\nIn .NET 10 MAUI, `ios:Page.UseSafeArea` was replaced with the cross-platform `Page.SafeAreaRegions` property. \n\nThe `SafeAreaRegions` enum offers values like `All` and `None`, and I can show the updated XAML syntax where you'd set `SafeAreaRegions=\"All\"` directly on the `ContentPage` instead of using the iOS-specific namespace prefix.","outputTokens":691,"requestId":"4828:24F9C3:A5DA67:C1CEAE:69F3FE46"},"id":"975921f9-70a8-4211-b8a6-b9f668d38546","timestamp":"2026-05-01T01:13:53.848Z","parentId":"b3d43216-2a40-4150-a08d-5b8e8ae50f5d"}
